stylometry: A simulation model is an electronic replica of a problem or situation that a company is trying to solve. Running models allows companies to solve "What If" situations without doing it in real life and wasting money they may not need to spend.  For example, a grocery store notices that they are experiencing exceptionally long lines lately and some customers become so fed up with waiting that they may leave without purchasing or they don't grab as many items during their shopping trips.  They want to see if purchasing more registers and hiring more cashiers will help decrease wait times and increase efficiency. They can also figure out the amount of registers they should have open during certain times of the day. Before purchasing more registers and hiring more cashiers, they can run a queuing model to see if wait times for lines will decrease. A queuing model takes into consideration, the amount of customers in a given time, the average amount of time that they wait in line, and the average amount of time it takes for them to be checked out by the cashier.  By running the queuing model they can determine if it is worth it to purchase more equipment and more cashiers.  Models can be used in all types of businesses and the prime objective for most is to increase productivity and reduce costs.
